'''Stephen O. Glosecki''' (died 4 April 2007) was a scholar of [[Old English]] language and literature. Glosecki was raised in [[Springfield, Illinois]], and educated at [[Sacred Heart-Griffin High School]]. He received his undergraduate degree from [[Beloit College]], and his Master's and Ph.D. degrees from [[University of California, Davis]].<ref name="obit">{{cite news|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/sj-r/obituary.aspx?n=stephen-o-glosecki&pid=87081136#sthash.vV3P5psS.dpuf|title=Stephen O. Glosecki Obituary|date=7 April 2007|work=[[The State Journal-Register]]|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> A professor of Old English at [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]], he was the author of books and articles on Old English literature, particularly on [[shamanism]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bjork|first1=Robert E.|last2=Niles|first2=John D.|title=A Beowulf Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SaFdpGdjvtoC&pg=PA196|year=1998|publisher=U of Nebraska P|isbn=9780803261501|page=196}}</ref> and [[folklore]], and was notable for his contributions to the anthropological study of early Germanic literature.<ref name=jurasinski>{{cite journal|last=Jurasinski|first=Stefan|year=2010|title=Rev. of Glosecki, ''Myth in Early Northwest Europe''|journal=[[Arthuriana]]|volume=20|issue=3|pages=122–24|jstor=23238265}}</ref> He died of cancer in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uab.edu/uabmagazine/spring2008/departments/books|title=Shelf Life|last=Till|first=Steven|year=2009|publisher=[[University of Alabama at Birmingham]]|accessdate=15 April 2014}}</ref> aged 55.<ref name="obit"/> A collection he edited, ''Myth in Early Northwest Europe'', was published posthumously; his introduction was called "lively and, in places, poetic", and his translations of some of the [[Anglo-Saxon metrical charms]] were praised as "fluent, vigorous".<ref name="Larrington2009"/>
==Selected publications== *''Shamanism and Old English Poetry''. New York: Garland, 1989.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bildhauer|first1=Bettina|last2=Mills|first2=Robert|title=The Monstrous Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5M7JElJtK8AC&pg=PA173|year=2003|publisher=U of Toronto P|isbn=9780802086679|page=173}}</ref> *''Myth in Early Northwest Europe'' (editor). Tempe: Arizona Center for Medieval and Renaissance Studies, in association with Brepols, 2007.<ref name=jurasinski/><ref name="Larrington2009">{{cite journal|last=Larrington|first=Carolyne|year=2009|title=Rev. of Glosecki (ed.), ''Myth in Early Northwest Europe''|journal=The English Historical Review|volume=CXXIV|issue=506|pages=114–116|issn=0013-8266|doi=10.1093/ehr/cen376|url=http://ehr.oxfordjournals.org/content/CXXIV/506/114.full.pdf}}</ref> *"Judith" (trans.). ''Old English Poetry: An Anthology.'' Ed. [[Roy Liuzza]]. Peterborough: Broadview, 2014.<ref>{{cite book|last=Liuzza|first=R.M.|title=Old English Poetry: An Anthology: A Broadview Anthology of British Literature Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HOoKAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA14|year=2014|publisher=Broadview|isbn=9781770484856|page=14}}</ref>
